00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:05,470
Ah! Fresh meat!

213
00:25:11,840 --> 00:25:16,516
- Amanda Thripp.
- Yes. Miss Trunchbull.

214
00:25:16,680 --> 00:25:22,198
What are those...
hanging down by your ears?

215
00:25:22,360 --> 00:25:26,831
- You mean my pigtails?
- Are you a pig?

216
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:31,994
- No. Miss Trunchbull.
- Do I allow pigs in my school?

217
00:25:32,160 --> 00:25:39,635
- My mommy thinks they're sweet.
- Your mommy is a twit!

218
00:25:39,800 --> 00:25:43,918
- Chop them off by tomorrow, or...
- But...

219
00:25:44,080 --> 00:25:47,789
But?
Did you say "but"?

220
00:25:47,960 --> 00:25:50,520
- Hammer throw.
- Definitely.

221
00:25:50,680 --> 00:25:53,752
I'll give you "but".

222
00:26:02,360 --> 00:26:05,477
- Good loft!
- Excellent release!

223
00:26:09,440 --> 00:26:12,796
Think she'll make the fence?

224
00:26:32,320 --> 00:26:36,199
Get to class before I throw you all
in the Chokey.

225
00:26:36,360 --> 00:26:40,956
- Lavender, what's my teacher like?
- Run. Run. Run!

226
00:26:41,120 --> 00:26:43,873
Faster! Get in!

227
00:26:45,160 --> 00:26:49,312
<i>Matilda's teacher, Miss Honey,</i>
<i>was one of those people -</i>

228
00:26:49,480 --> 00:26:53,359
<i>- who appreciates every child</i>
<i>forwho she or he is.</i>

229
00:26:53,520 --> 00:26:58,753
- I scooped these up for you.
- How lovely. Thank you, Amanda.

230
00:26:58,920 --> 00:27:02,629
We have a new student with us today.

231
00:27:02,800 --> 00:27:07,271
This is Matilda Wormwood.
I'd like you to sit with Lavender.

232
00:27:07,440 --> 00:27:13,470
You all know how scary the first day
of school is. So be nice to Matilda.

233
00:27:13,640 --> 00:27:18,430
Could you get her workbook, please?
You can sit down.

234
00:27:18,600 --> 00:27:21,797
<i>Miss Honey was a wonderful teacher.</i>

235
00:27:21,960 --> 00:27:28,069
<i>But her life was not as beautiful</i>
<i>as it seemed. She had a dark secret.</i>

236
00:27:28,240 --> 00:27:33,519
<i>Though it caused her pain, it didn't</i>
<i>interfere with her teaching.</i>

237
00:27:33,680 --> 00:27:40,199
You've come on a good day. We're
going to review what we've learned.

238
00:27:40,360 --> 00:27:47,596
If you know an answer,
just raise your hand.

239
00:27:47,760 --> 00:27:52,436
We've been working on our times
tables. Who'd like to demonstrate?

240
00:27:53,400 --> 00:27:57,916
Let's do some together.

241
00:27:59,040 --> 00:28:02,032
- 2 x 4 is?
- 8.

242
00:28:02,200 --> 00:28:05,351
- 2 x 6 is?
- 12.

243
00:28:05,520 --> 00:28:08,592
- 2 x 9 is?
- 18.

244
00:28:08,760 --> 00:28:14,039
Soon you'll be able to do them all,
whether it's 2 x 7...

245
00:28:14,200 --> 00:28:18,751
- 14.
- Or 13 x 379.

246
00:28:18,920 --> 00:28:22,356
4,927.

247
00:28:23,880 --> 00:28:28,112
- I beg your pardon?
- I think that's the answer.

248
00:28:28,280 --> 00:28:32,831
13 x 379 is 4.927.

249
00:28:50,760 --> 00:28:54,196
- It is.
- Wow...

250
00:28:58,120 --> 00:29:05,674
- You can multiply big numbers?
- I read a book on mathematics.

251
00:29:07,320 --> 00:29:11,313
- You like to read?
- Yes. I love to read.

252
00:29:11,480 --> 00:29:19,512
- What do you like to read?
- I've been reading Darls Chickens.

253
00:29:19,680 --> 00:29:24,196
Charles Dickens.
I could read him every day.

254
00:29:24,360 --> 00:29:28,319
So could I.

255
00:29:29,600 --> 00:29:35,835
All right, take out your workbooks
and let's start with section three.

256
00:29:42,080 --> 00:29:45,197
I'll be back in a moment.

257
00:29:55,480 --> 00:30:00,156
Gotcha! Right in the neck.

258
00:30:02,120 --> 00:30:04,839
Come in.

259
00:30:06,920 --> 00:30:09,753
Almost got you.

260
00:30:09,920 --> 00:30:13,708
Good to see you, Jen.

261
00:30:13,880 --> 00:30:17,668
Time for one of our
little heart-to-hearts?

262
00:30:20,080 --> 00:30:25,313
It's about the new girl in my class,
Matilda Wormwood.

263
00:30:25,480 --> 00:30:28,040
Her father says she's a real wart.

264
00:30:28,200 --> 00:30:31,988
A carbuncle. A blister.
A pustule of malignant ooze.

265
00:30:32,160 --> 00:30:38,315
- Matilda is sweet and very bright.
- A bright child?

266
00:30:38,480 --> 00:30:43,429
- She can multiply large sums.
- So can a calculator.

267
00:30:43,600 --> 00:30:49,675
I think she might be happier
in an older and more advanced class.

268
00:30:49,840 --> 00:30:54,630
You can't handle the little viper,
so you're trying to get rid of her.

269
00:30:54,800 --> 00:30:59,396
- No...
- Typical, slothful cowardice!

270
00:30:59,560 --> 00:31:06,272
The distance the shot-put goes
depends on your effort.

271
00:31:06,440 --> 00:31:12,709
If you can't handle the little brat,
I'II lock her in the Chokey!

272
00:31:14,680 --> 00:31:17,877
- Get it?
- Yes. Ma'am.

273
00:31:18,040 --> 00:31:21,476
Everything I do
is for your own good.

274
00:31:21,640 --> 00:31:25,952
And the good of
those putrescent, little children!

275
00:31:49,920 --> 00:31:53,833
- Mom. I'm home.
<i>- How was school?</i>

276
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:59,279
- I get to do sixth grade work.
- Hold on a minute.

277
00:31:59,440 --> 00:32:04,468
- Can't you see I'm on the phone?
- You just asked me how school was.

278
00:32:05,920 --> 00:32:10,675
- The baby wasn't his.
- Well, it was really great.

279
00:32:10,840 --> 00:32:15,470
- No way. They have to be implants.
- The principal is insane.

280
00:32:15,640 --> 00:32:21,875
- She threw a girl over the fence.
- You should wax yours, too.

281
00:32:22,040 --> 00:32:24,952
I have the most wonderful teacher.

282
00:32:25,120 --> 00:32:30,478
Mine are driving me crazy.
Six hours at school is not enough.

283
00:32:30,640 --> 00:32:32,710
I'll say.

284
00:32:32,880 --> 00:32:38,352
Awhack to the belly.
A smack to the face. Burns is hurt.

285
00:32:38,520 --> 00:32:40,954
Saved by the bell.

286
00:32:41,120 --> 00:32:45,716
- Packages at this hour?
- Come here.

287
00:32:49,040 --> 00:32:53,750
- Hello.
- We don't give money, charity...

288
00:32:53,920 --> 00:32:58,118
I'm Jennifer Honey.
I'm Matilda's teacher.

289
00:32:58,280 --> 00:33:04,196
What's she done now?
You! Go to your room, right now!

290
00:33:04,360 --> 00:33:10,117
- She's your problem now.
- There is no problem.

291
00:33:10,280 --> 00:33:13,875
Then beat it. We're watching TV.

292
00:33:14,040 --> 00:33:21,071
If a TV show is more important than
Matilda, you shouldn't be a parent.

293
00:33:21,240 --> 00:33:24,391
Turn it off and listen to me.

294
00:33:28,400 --> 00:33:33,633
Come on in. Get this over with.
Mrs. Wormwood won't like this.

295
00:33:36,160 --> 00:33:38,879
- Close the door.
- Who is it?

296
00:33:39,040 --> 00:33:42,749
Some teacher.

297
00:33:43,680 --> 00:33:48,151
- What did you do that for?
- What do you want?

298
00:33:48,320 --> 00:33:53,792
- Matilda has a brilliant mind.
- Yeah, right. Give me a beer.

299
00:33:53,960 --> 00:33:58,397
- Her math skills are extraordinary.
- Do you want one?

300
00:33:58,560 --> 00:34:05,159
No thank you. She's reading material
that I didn't see until college.

301
00:34:05,320 --> 00:34:07,356
College!

302
00:34:07,520 --> 00:34:12,514
With private instruction, she'd be
ready for college in a few years.

303
00:34:12,680 --> 00:34:18,437
A girl does not get anywhere
by acting intelligent.

304
00:34:18,600 --> 00:34:23,993
Look at you and me.
You chose books. I chose looks.

305
00:34:24,160 --> 00:34:32,317
I have a nice house and a husband.
You teach children their ABC's.

306
00:34:32,480 --> 00:34:35,756
You want Matilda to go to college?

307
00:34:35,920 --> 00:34:40,118
I didn't go to college.
I don't know anybody who did.

308
00:34:40,280 --> 00:34:43,590
A bunch of hippies
and cesspool salesmen.

309
00:34:43,760 --> 00:34:47,309
Don't sneer at educated people.

310
00:34:47,480 --> 00:34:52,679
If you became ill, your doctor
would be a college graduate.

311
00:34:52,840 --> 00:34:57,994
If you were sued, your lawyer
would have gone to college, too.

312
00:34:58,160 --> 00:35:03,154
Sued by who?
Who have you been talking to?

313
00:35:03,320 --> 00:35:06,915
Nobody.

314
00:35:07,080 --> 00:35:13,076
I can see
we're not going to agree. Are we?

315
00:35:13,240 --> 00:35:17,472
I'm sorry
I burst in on you like this.

316
00:35:19,520 --> 00:35:23,229
We ought to sue her
for interrupting our show.

317
00:35:24,480 --> 00:35:28,393
- Why's he standing in the middle?
- Because it's over.

318
00:35:28,560 --> 00:35:32,394
- Thank you.
- See you tomorrow.

319
00:35:33,760 --> 00:35:39,517
- Who won?
- I don't know. You shut it off.

320
00:35:39,680 --> 00:35:40,480
<i>The entire school will go</i>
<i>to the assembly room immediately!</i>

321
00:35:40,480 --> 00:35:45,634
<i>The entire school will go</i>
<i>to the assembly room immediately!</i>

322
00:35:45,800 --> 00:35:48,109
Sit!

323
00:35:48,280 --> 00:35:50,999
- What's up?
- Beats me.

324
00:35:54,120 --> 00:35:57,908
Bruce Bogtrotter.

325
00:36:04,800 --> 00:36:08,076
Would little Brucey come up here?

326
00:36:19,760 --> 00:36:22,433
He lives on my block.

327
00:36:26,920 --> 00:36:34,873
This boy, Bruce Bogtrotter,
is a vicious sneak thief.

328
00:36:35,040 --> 00:36:39,875
- You're a disgusting criminal.
- What are you talking about?

329
00:36:40,040 --> 00:36:42,679
Chocolate cake.

330
00:36:42,840 --> 00:36:49,154
You slithered like a serpent
into the kitchen and ate my snack!

331
00:36:49,320 --> 00:36:52,596
Do you deny it?

332
00:36:55,720 --> 00:36:58,439
Confess!

333
00:36:58,600 --> 00:37:06,280
- I can't remember a specific cake.
- This one was mine.

334
00:37:06,440 --> 00:37:11,753
- It was the best cake in the world.
- My mom's is better.

335
00:37:11,920 --> 00:37:18,359
How can you be sure
unless you have another piece?

336
00:37:19,920 --> 00:37:23,435
Sit down, Bog.

337
00:37:39,600 --> 00:37:46,517
Here we go.
Smells chocolatey, eh?

338
00:37:46,680 --> 00:37:49,877
Now. Eat it!

339
00:37:51,880 --> 00:37:54,872
I don't want any. Thank you.

340
00:37:55,040 --> 00:37:58,316
Eat it!

341
00:37:59,040 --> 00:38:01,554
Don't eat it.

342
00:38:01,720 --> 00:38:04,996
- She wouldn't give him cake.
- It's poison.

343
00:38:34,720 --> 00:38:39,589
- You look like you enjoyed that.
- Yes. Ma'am.

344
00:38:39,760 --> 00:38:44,788
- You must have some more.
- No thanks.

345
00:38:44,960 --> 00:38:49,272
But you'll hurt the cook's feelings.

346
00:38:52,160 --> 00:38:56,950
She made this cakejust for you.

347
00:38:59,280 --> 00:39:02,795
Her sweat and blood
went into this cake.

348
00:39:02,960 --> 00:39:09,035
You will not leave this platform
until you have eaten the whole cake!

349
00:39:09,200 --> 00:39:14,593
- The whole cake! See you at lunch.
- Thank you, Cookie.

350
00:39:14,760 --> 00:39:20,039
You wanted cake, you got cake.
Now eat it!

351
00:39:33,200 --> 00:39:35,714
Poor Brucey.

352
00:40:06,880 --> 00:40:09,075
He's going to puke.

353
00:40:09,240 --> 00:40:14,268
- I can't look. Is he going to puke?
- Without a doubt.

354
00:40:21,680 --> 00:40:26,834
- Bruce looks real bad.
- Give up?

355
00:40:29,920 --> 00:40:33,674
You can do it, Brucey!

356
00:40:35,320 --> 00:40:38,198
Yeah, you can do it!

357
00:40:38,360 --> 00:40:40,669
Go. Bruce!

358
00:40:47,200 --> 00:40:49,998
Silence!

359
00:40:56,600 --> 00:41:00,718
Silence!

360
00:41:01,720 --> 00:41:04,188
Stop! Silence!

361
00:41:26,720 --> 00:41:32,909
The entire assembly
will stay five hours after school!

362
00:41:33,080 --> 00:41:39,315
Any children who object will go
straight into the Chokey. Together!

363
00:41:47,720 --> 00:41:52,077
<i>Code R's the official way of saying</i>
<i>we've caught a bad one.</i>

364
00:41:57,720 --> 00:42:02,669
- Where were you?
- Miss Trunchbull kept us late.

365
00:42:02,840 --> 00:42:08,756
That's a lie! The packages were left
outside because you weren't here.

366
00:42:08,920 --> 00:42:14,552
You get all this stuff from
catalogues and I don't get anything!

367
00:42:14,720 --> 00:42:18,076
It's car parts. It's business.

368
00:42:18,240 --> 00:42:23,109
- Why isn't it sent to the office?
- The cops are watching the office.

369
00:42:23,280 --> 00:42:26,397
The cops are watching the house.

370
00:42:26,560 --> 00:42:33,159
- They're parked outside, right now.
- Those are speedboat salesmen.

371
00:42:33,320 --> 00:42:36,676
- Really nice guys.
- Cops.

372
00:42:38,760 --> 00:42:42,833
Speedboats?
There are no lakes around here.

373
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:48,950
- Some people go away on weekends.
- And some people are cops.

374
00:42:49,120 --> 00:42:57,312
They're not cops!
Go to bed, you lying little earwig!

375
00:42:57,480 --> 00:43:02,235
<i>With the FBI watching her father,</i>
<i>and the Trunchbull at school. - </i>

376
00:43:02,400 --> 00:43:06,313
<i>- it was a rare moment when Matilda</i>
<i>couldjust play.</i>

377
00:43:06,480 --> 00:43:09,836
Afrog! Afrog! Afrog!

378
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:13,436
- What is it. Lavender?
- Afrog!

379
00:43:15,320 --> 00:43:18,756
- It's a salamander.
- It's a chameleon.

380
00:43:18,920 --> 00:43:23,118
"Any of the semiaquatic salamanders
from the genus triturus."

381
00:43:23,280 --> 00:43:28,718
"Some are brightly coloured
and secrete irritating substances."

382
00:43:30,920 --> 00:43:35,436
Useless, flaming car!

383
00:43:37,800 --> 00:43:41,156
Wormwood! Sell me a lemon!

384
00:43:41,320 --> 00:43:45,233
You're heading for the Chokey!
Teach you a lesson!

385
00:43:45,400 --> 00:43:49,951
You and your father think
you can make a fool out of me!

386
00:43:50,120 --> 00:43:54,113
- I'm nothing like my father!
- You're the spitting image!

387
00:43:54,280 --> 00:43:58,280
The apple never rots
far from the tree!

388
00:43:58,520 --> 00:44:02,832
- Miss Honey!
- Trunchbull is teaching our class.

389
00:44:03,000 --> 00:44:06,629
She'll be here any second!

390
00:44:07,400 --> 00:44:12,952
Make sure the water is cold.
Cover the fish!

391
00:44:13,120 --> 00:44:16,237
Put away the art projects.

392
00:44:16,400 --> 00:44:20,188
<i>Most great ideas</i>
<i>come from careful planning.</i>

393
00:44:20,360 --> 00:44:24,831
<i>But sometimes.</i>
<i>Theyjustjump out at you.</i>

394
00:44:28,320 --> 00:44:33,599
Last time, you forgot yourselves.
Don't speak unless you're spoken to.

395
00:44:33,760 --> 00:44:39,790
- Don't laugh. Don't breathe loudly.
- Don't breathe at all.

396
00:44:41,920 --> 00:44:45,117
Good morning, Miss Trunchbull.

397
00:44:47,160 --> 00:44:49,913
Sit!

398
00:44:52,720 --> 00:44:54,915
Shoo.

399
00:44:56,800 --> 00:45:01,590
I don't understand
why children are so disgusting.

400
00:45:01,760 --> 00:45:04,911
They're like insects.

401
00:45:05,080 --> 00:45:08,390
They should be got rid of.

402
00:45:11,440 --> 00:45:18,790
The perfect school is one in which
there are no children.

403
00:45:19,640 --> 00:45:22,950
Do you agree, Miss Honey?

404
00:45:25,640 --> 00:45:30,111
You! Front of the class!

405
00:45:35,880 --> 00:45:38,792
Are you okay?

406
00:45:38,960 --> 00:45:44,159
Next time I tell you
to empty your pockets, do it faster!

407
00:45:44,320 --> 00:45:48,279
This could be the most
interesting thing you've ever done.

408
00:45:52,720 --> 00:45:56,633
Sit down, you squirming worm!

409
00:46:06,920 --> 00:46:09,309
Get up!

410
00:46:10,880 --> 00:46:16,910
- Can you spell?
- We can spell "difficulty".

411
00:46:17,080 --> 00:46:22,791
- You can't spell "difficulty".
- She taught us with a poem.

412
00:46:22,960 --> 00:46:26,350
How sweet. What poem is that?

413
00:46:26,520 --> 00:46:32,436
Mrs. D. Mrs. I.
Mrs. F. F. I.

414
00:46:32,600 --> 00:46:37,754
Mrs. C. Mrs. U.
Mrs. L. T. Y.

415
00:46:37,920 --> 00:46:44,268
Why are all these women married?
You teach spelling, not poetry!

416
00:46:49,760 --> 00:46:54,197
Why do small children
take so long to grow up?

417
00:46:54,360 --> 00:46:58,319
They do it deliberately,
just to annoy me.

418
00:47:12,840 --> 00:47:15,559
What's funny?

419
00:47:15,720 --> 00:47:20,748
Spit it out! I like ajoke
as well as the next fat person.

420
00:47:26,760 --> 00:47:29,274
It's a snake!

421
00:47:30,280 --> 00:47:33,033
It's a snake!

422
00:47:33,960 --> 00:47:37,236
One of you tried to poison me. Who?

423
00:47:38,480 --> 00:47:41,756
Matilda! I knew it.

424
00:47:41,920 --> 00:47:46,550
- It's not a snake. It's a newt.
- What did you say?

425
00:47:46,720 --> 00:47:53,398
- It's a newt. Miss Trunchbull.
- Stand up! You did this.

426
00:47:53,560 --> 00:47:57,872
- No. Miss Trunchbull.
- Did you have accomplices?

427
00:47:59,320 --> 00:48:05,555
- I didn't do it!
- You thought you'd pay me back?

428
00:48:05,720 --> 00:48:09,952
- Well, I'II pay you back.
- For what. Miss Trunchbull?

429
00:48:10,120 --> 00:48:15,433
- For this newt, you pissworm!
- I'm telling you, I didn't do it!

430
00:48:15,600 --> 00:48:21,516
Anyway, I'm big and you're small,
I'm right and you're wrong.

431
00:48:21,680 --> 00:48:26,356
There's nothing you can do about it.
You're a liar and a scoundrel.

432
00:48:26,520 --> 00:48:32,436
Your father is a cheat! You're the
most corrupt low-lifes in history!

433
00:48:32,600 --> 00:48:35,751
Am I wrong? I'm never wrong.

434
00:48:35,920 --> 00:48:41,756
In this classroom. In this school,
I am God!

435
00:49:11,520 --> 00:49:14,159
- You!
- I didn't move!

436
00:49:14,320 --> 00:49:19,314
- You did this.
- She was sitting way over here.

437
00:49:19,480 --> 00:49:24,110
I'll be watching you.
Each and every one.

438
00:49:24,280 --> 00:49:28,956
When you turn the corner,
when you get your smelly coats.

439
00:49:29,120 --> 00:49:34,069
When you skip merrily to lunch.
I'll be watching you. All of you.

440
00:49:34,240 --> 00:49:37,471
And especially you!

441
00:49:47,600 --> 00:49:52,549
- Thanks for not telling.
- Best friends don't tell.

